vectorData.altText: 12. What term describes the position of an organ that develops initially within the abdominal cavity, attached to the body wall by a mesentery, but that ultimately becomes fixed to the posterior body wall?
That's right! Secondarily retroperitoneal organs develop initially in an intraperitoneal position, but ultimately become fused to the posterior body wall.

During embryonic development, the GI tract begins in an intraperitoneal position (Fig. A). 
Certain portions of the GI tract become fixed to the posterior body wall (Fig. B). They are described as being secondarily retroperitoneal.
How does this happen?
